10610 
10611 // Return true iff the given array filler may depend on the element index.
10612 static bool MaybeElementDependentArrayFiller(const Expr *FillerExpr) {
10613  // For now, just allow non-class value-initialization and initialization
10614  // lists comprised of them.
10615  if (isa<ImplicitValueInitExpr>(FillerExpr))
10616  return false;
10617  if (const InitListExpr *ILE = dyn_cast<InitListExpr>(FillerExpr)) {
10618  for (unsigned I = 0, E = ILE->getNumInits(); I != E; ++I) {
10619  if (MaybeElementDependentArrayFiller(ILE->getInit(I)))
10620  return true;
10621  }
10622  return false;
10623  }
10624  return true;
10625 }
10626 
10627 bool ArrayExprEvaluator::VisitInitListExpr(const InitListExpr *E,
10628  QualType AllocType) {
10629  const ConstantArrayType *CAT = Info.Ctx.getAsConstantArrayType(
10630  AllocType.isNull() ? E->getType() : AllocType);
10631  if (!CAT)
10632  return Error(E);
10633 
10634  // C++11 [dcl.init.string]p1: A char array [...] can be initialized by [...]
10635  // an appropriately-typed string literal enclosed in braces.
10636  if (E->isStringLiteralInit()) {
10637  auto *SL = dyn_cast<StringLiteral>(E->getInit(0)->IgnoreParenImpCasts());
10638  // FIXME: Support ObjCEncodeExpr here once we support it in
10639  // ArrayExprEvaluator generally.
10640  if (!SL)
10641  return Error(E);
10642  return VisitStringLiteral(SL, AllocType);
10643  }
10644  // Any other transparent list init will need proper handling of the
10645  // AllocType; we can't just recurse to the inner initializer.
10646  assert(!E->isTransparent() &&
10647  "transparent array list initialization is not string literal init?");
10648 
10649  bool Success = true;
10650 
10651  assert((!Result.isArray() || Result.getArrayInitializedElts() == 0) &&
10652  "zero-initialized array shouldn't have any initialized elts");
10653  APValue Filler;
10654  if (Result.isArray() && Result.hasArrayFiller())
10655  Filler = Result.getArrayFiller();
10656 
10657  unsigned NumEltsToInit = E->getNumInits();
10658  unsigned NumElts = CAT->getSize().getZExtValue();
10659  const Expr *FillerExpr = E->hasArrayFiller() ? E->getArrayFiller() : nullptr;
10660 
10661  // If the initializer might depend on the array index, run it for each
10662  // array element.
10663  if (NumEltsToInit != NumElts && MaybeElementDependentArrayFiller(FillerExpr))
10664  NumEltsToInit = NumElts;
10665 
10666  LLVM_DEBUG(llvm::dbgs() << "The number of elements to initialize: "
10667  << NumEltsToInit << ".\n");
10668 
10669  Result = APValue(APValue::UninitArray(), NumEltsToInit, NumElts);
10670 
10671  // If the array was previously zero-initialized, preserve the
10672  // zero-initialized values.
10673  if (Filler.hasValue()) {
10674  for (unsigned I = 0, E = Result.getArrayInitializedElts(); I != E; ++I)
10675  Result.getArrayInitializedElt(I) = Filler;
10676  if (Result.hasArrayFiller())
10677  Result.getArrayFiller() = Filler;
10678  }
10679 
10680  LValue Subobject = This;
10681  Subobject.addArray(Info, E, CAT);
10682  for (unsigned Index = 0; Index != NumEltsToInit; ++Index) {
10683  const Expr *Init =
10684  Index < E->getNumInits() ? E->getInit(Index) : FillerExpr;
10685  if (!EvaluateInPlace(Result.getArrayInitializedElt(Index),
10686  Info, Subobject, Init) ||
10687  !HandleLValueArrayAdjustment(Info, Init, Subobject,
10688  CAT->getElementType(), 1)) {
10689  if (!Info.noteFailure())
10690  return false;
10691  Success = false;
10692  }
10693  }
10694 
10695  if (!Result.hasArrayFiller())
10696  return Success;
10697 
10698  // If we get here, we have a trivial filler, which we can just evaluate
10699  // once and splat over the rest of the array elements.
10700  assert(FillerExpr && "no array filler for incomplete init list");
10701  return EvaluateInPlace(Result.getArrayFiller(), Info, Subobject,
10702  FillerExpr) && Success;
10703 }
10704 
10705 bool ArrayExprEvaluator::VisitArrayInitLoopExpr(const ArrayInitLoopExpr *E) {
10706  LValue CommonLV;
10707  if (E->getCommonExpr() &&
10708  !Evaluate(Info.CurrentCall->createTemporary(
10709  E->getCommonExpr(),
10710  getStorageType(Info.Ctx, E->getCommonExpr()),
10711  ScopeKind::FullExpression, CommonLV),
10712  Info, E->getCommonExpr()->getSourceExpr()))
10713  return false;
10714 
10715  auto *CAT = cast<ConstantArrayType>(E->getType()->castAsArrayTypeUnsafe());
10716 
10717  uint64_t Elements = CAT->getSize().getZExtValue();
10718  Result = APValue(APValue::UninitArray(), Elements, Elements);
10719 
10720  LValue Subobject = This;
10721  Subobject.addArray(Info, E, CAT);
10722 
10723  bool Success = true;
10724  for (EvalInfo::ArrayInitLoopIndex Index(Info); Index != Elements; ++Index) {
10725  if (!EvaluateInPlace(Result.getArrayInitializedElt(Index),
10726  Info, Subobject, E->getSubExpr()) ||
10727  !HandleLValueArrayAdjustment(Info, E, Subobject,
10728  CAT->getElementType(), 1)) {
10729  if (!Info.noteFailure())
10730  return false;
10731  Success = false;
10732  }
10733  }
10734 
10735  return Success;
10736 }
10737 
10738 bool ArrayExprEvaluator::VisitCXXConstructExpr(const CXXConstructExpr *E) {
10739  return VisitCXXConstructExpr(E, This, &Result, E->getType());
10740 }
10741 
10742 bool ArrayExprEvaluator::VisitCXXConstructExpr(const CXXConstructExpr *E,
10743  const LValue &Subobject,
10744  APValue *Value,
10745  QualType Type) {
10746  bool HadZeroInit = Value->hasValue();
10747 
10748  if (const ConstantArrayType *CAT = Info.Ctx.getAsConstantArrayType(Type)) {
10749  unsigned FinalSize = CAT->getSize().getZExtValue();
10750 
10751  // Preserve the array filler if we had prior zero-initialization.
10752  APValue Filler =
10753  HadZeroInit && Value->hasArrayFiller() ? Value->getArrayFiller()
10754  : APValue();
10755 
10756  *Value = APValue(APValue::UninitArray(), 0, FinalSize);
10757  if (FinalSize == 0)
10758  return true;
10759 
10760  LValue ArrayElt = Subobject;
10761  ArrayElt.addArray(Info, E, CAT);
10762  // We do the whole initialization in two passes, first for just one element,
10763  // then for the whole array. It's possible we may find out we can't do const
10764  // init in the first pass, in which case we avoid allocating a potentially
10765  // large array. We don't do more passes because expanding array requires
10766  // copying the data, which is wasteful.
10767  for (const unsigned N : {1u, FinalSize}) {
10768  unsigned OldElts = Value->getArrayInitializedElts();
10769  if (OldElts == N)
10770  break;
10771 
10772  // Expand the array to appropriate size.
10773  APValue NewValue(APValue::UninitArray(), N, FinalSize);
10774  for (unsigned I = 0; I < OldElts; ++I)
10775  NewValue.getArrayInitializedElt(I).swap(
10776  Value->getArrayInitializedElt(I));
10777  Value->swap(NewValue);
10778 
10779  if (HadZeroInit)
10780  for (unsigned I = OldElts; I < N; ++I)
10781  Value->getArrayInitializedElt(I) = Filler;
10782 
10783  // Initialize the elements.
10784  for (unsigned I = OldElts; I < N; ++I) {
10785  if (!VisitCXXConstructExpr(E, ArrayElt,
10786  &Value->getArrayInitializedElt(I),
10787  CAT->getElementType()) ||
10788  !HandleLValueArrayAdjustment(Info, E, ArrayElt,
10789  CAT->getElementType(), 1))
10790  return false;
10791  // When checking for const initilization any diagnostic is considered
10792  // an error.
10793  if (Info.EvalStatus.Diag && !Info.EvalStatus.Diag->empty() &&
10794  !Info.keepEvaluatingAfterFailure())
10795  return false;
10796  }
10797  }
10798 
10799  return true;
10800  }
10801 
10802  if (!Type->isRecordType())
10803  return Error(E);
10804 
10805  return RecordExprEvaluator(Info, Subobject, *Value)
10806  .VisitCXXConstructExpr(E, Type);
10807 }
10808 
10809 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//
10810 // Integer Evaluation
10811 //
10812 // As a GNU extension, we support casting pointers to sufficiently-wide integer
10813 // types and back in constant folding. Integer values are thus represented
10814 // either as an integer-valued APValue, or as an lvalue-valued APValue.
10815 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//
10816 
10817 namespace {
10818 class IntExprEvaluator
10819  : public ExprEvaluatorBase<IntExprEvaluator> {
10820  APValue &Result;
10821 public:
10822  IntExprEvaluator(EvalInfo &info, APValue &result)
10823  : ExprEvaluatorBaseTy(info), Result(result) {}
10824 
10825  bool Success(const llvm::APSInt &SI, const Expr *E, APValue &Result) {
10826  assert(E->getType()->isIntegralOrEnumerationType() &&
10827  "Invalid evaluation result.");
10828  assert(SI.isSigned() == E->getType()->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType() &&
10829  "Invalid evaluation result.");
10830  assert(SI.getBitWidth() == Info.Ctx.getIntWidth(E->getType()) &&
10831  "Invalid evaluation result.");
10832  Result = APValue(SI);
10833  return true;
10834  }
10835  bool Success(const llvm::APSInt &SI, const Expr *E) {
10836  return Success(SI, E, Result);
10837  }
10838 
10839  bool Success(const llvm::APInt &I, const Expr *E, APValue &Result) {
10840  assert(E->getType()->isIntegralOrEnumerationType() &&
10841  "Invalid evaluation result.");
10842  assert(I.getBitWidth() == Info.Ctx.getIntWidth(E->getType()) &&
10843  "Invalid evaluation result.");
10844  Result = APValue(APSInt(I));
10845  Result.getInt().setIsUnsigned(
10846  E->getType()->isUnsignedIntegerOrEnumerationType());
10847  return true;
10848  }
10849  bool Success(const llvm::APInt &I, const Expr *E) {
10850  return Success(I, E, Result);
10851  }
10852 
10853  bool Success(uint64_t Value, const Expr *E, APValue &Result) {
10854  assert(E->getType()->isIntegralOrEnumerationType() &&
10855  "Invalid evaluation result.");
10856  Result = APValue(Info.Ctx.MakeIntValue(Value, E->getType()));
10857  return true;
10858  }
10859  bool Success(uint64_t Value, const Expr *E) {
10860  return Success(Value, E, Result);
10861  }
10862 
10863  bool Success(CharUnits Size, const Expr *E) {
10864  return Success(Size.getQuantity(), E);
10865  }
10866 
10867  bool Success(const APValue &V, const Expr *E) {
10868  if (V.isLValue() || V.isAddrLabelDiff() || V.isIndeterminate()) {
10869  Result = V;
10870  return true;
10871  }
10872  return Success(V.getInt(), E);
10873  }
10874 
10875  bool ZeroInitialization(const Expr *E) { return Success(0, E); }
10876 
10877  //===--------------------------------------------------------------------===//
10878  // Visitor Methods
10879  //===--------------------------------------------------------------------===//
10880 
10881  bool VisitIntegerLiteral(const IntegerLiteral *E) {
10882  return Success(E->getValue(), E);
10883  }
10884  bool VisitCharacterLiteral(const CharacterLiteral *E) {
10885  return Success(E->getValue(), E);
10886  }
10887 
10888  bool CheckReferencedDecl(const Expr *E, const Decl *D);
10889  bool VisitDeclRefExpr(const DeclRefExpr *E) {
10890  if (CheckReferencedDecl(E, E->getDecl()))
10891  return true;
10892 
10893  return ExprEvaluatorBaseTy::VisitDeclRefExpr(E);
10894  }
10895  bool VisitMemberExpr(const MemberExpr *E) {
10896  if (CheckReferencedDecl(E, E->getMemberDecl())) {
10897  VisitIgnoredBaseExpression(E->getBase());
10898  return true;
10899  }
10900 
10901  return ExprEvaluatorBaseTy::VisitMemberExpr(E);
10902  }

10906  bool VisitBinaryOperator(const BinaryOperator *E);
10907  bool VisitOffsetOfExpr(const OffsetOfExpr *E);
10908  bool VisitUnaryOperator(const UnaryOperator *E);
10909

10911  bool VisitUnaryExprOrTypeTraitExpr(const UnaryExprOrTypeTraitExpr *E);
10912

10914  return Success(E->getValue(), E);
10915  }

10918  return Success(E->getValue(), E);
10919  }
10920

10922  if (Info.ArrayInitIndex == uint64_t(-1)) {
10923  // We were asked to evaluate this subexpression independent of the
10924  // enclosing ArrayInitLoopExpr. We can't do that.
10925  Info.FFDiag(E);
10926  return false;
10927  }
10928  return Success(Info.ArrayInitIndex, E);
10929  }
10930 
10931  // Note, GNU defines __null as an integer, not a pointer.
10932  bool VisitGNUNullExpr(const GNUNullExpr *E) {
10933  return ZeroInitialization(E);
10934  }
10935 
10936  bool VisitTypeTraitExpr(const TypeTraitExpr *E) {
10937  return Success(E->getValue(), E);
10938  }
10939

10941  return Success(E->getValue(), E);
10942  }
10943 
10944  bool VisitExpressionTraitExpr(const ExpressionTraitExpr *E) {
10945  return Success(E->getValue(), E);
10946  }
10947 
10948  bool VisitUnaryReal(const UnaryOperator *E);
10949  bool VisitUnaryImag(const UnaryOperator *E);
10950 
10951  bool VisitCXXNoexceptExpr(const CXXNoexceptExpr *E);
10952  bool VisitSizeOfPackExpr(const SizeOfPackExpr *E);
10953  bool VisitSourceLocExpr(const SourceLocExpr *E);
10954  bool VisitConceptSpecializationExpr(const ConceptSpecializationExpr *E);
10955  bool VisitRequiresExpr(const RequiresExpr *E);
10956  // FIXME: Missing: array subscript of vector, member of vector
10957 
10958  bool VisitSYCLBuiltinNumFieldsExpr(const SYCLBuiltinNumFieldsExpr *E) {
10959  return Success(E->getNumFields(), E);
10960  }
10961  bool VisitSYCLBuiltinNumBasesExpr(const SYCLBuiltinNumBasesExpr *E) {
10962  return Success(E->getNumBases(), E);
10963  }

11009 
11010 /// EvaluateIntegerOrLValue - Evaluate an rvalue integral-typed expression, and
11011 /// produce either the integer value or a pointer.
11012 ///
11013 /// GCC has a heinous extension which folds casts between pointer types and
11014 /// pointer-sized integral types. We support this by allowing the evaluation of
11015 /// an integer rvalue to produce a pointer (represented as an lvalue) instead.
11016 /// Some simple arithmetic on such values is supported (they are treated much
11017 /// like char*).
11018 static bool EvaluateIntegerOrLValue(const Expr *E, APValue &Result,
11019  EvalInfo &Info) {
11020  assert(!E->isValueDependent());
11021  assert(E->isPRValue() && E->getType()->isIntegralOrEnumerationType());
11022  return IntExprEvaluator(Info, Result).Visit(E);
11023 }
11024 
11025 static bool EvaluateInteger(const Expr *E, APSInt &Result, EvalInfo &Info) {
11026  assert(!E->isValueDependent());
11027  APValue Val;
11028  if (!EvaluateIntegerOrLValue(E, Val, Info))
11029  return false;
11030  if (!Val.isInt()) {
11031  // FIXME: It would be better to produce the diagnostic for casting
11032  // a pointer to an integer.
11033  Info.FFDiag(E, diag::note_invalid_subexpr_in_const_expr);
11034  return false;
11035  }
11036  Result = Val.getInt();
11037  return true;
11038 }
11039 
11040 bool IntExprEvaluator::VisitSourceLocExpr(const SourceLocExpr *E) {
11041  APValue Evaluated = E->EvaluateInContext(
11042  Info.Ctx, Info.CurrentCall->CurSourceLocExprScope.getDefaultExpr());
11043  return Success(Evaluated, E);
11044 }
11045 
11046 static bool EvaluateFixedPoint(const Expr *E, APFixedPoint &Result,
11047  EvalInfo &Info) {
11048  assert(!E->isValueDependent());
11049  if (E->getType()->isFixedPointType()) {
11050  APValue Val;
11051  if (!FixedPointExprEvaluator(Info, Val).Visit(E))
11052  return false;
11053  if (!Val.isFixedPoint())
11054  return false;
11055 
11056  Result = Val.getFixedPoint();
11057  return true;
11058  }
11059  return false;
11060 }
11061 
11062 static bool EvaluateFixedPointOrInteger(const Expr *E, APFixedPoint &Result,
11063  EvalInfo &Info) {
11064  assert(!E->isValueDependent());
11065  if (E->getType()->isIntegerType()) {
11066  auto FXSema = Info.Ctx.getFixedPointSemantics(E->getType());
11067  APSInt Val;
11068  if (!EvaluateInteger(E, Val, Info))
11069  return false;
11070  Result = APFixedPoint(Val, FXSema);
11071  return true;
11072  } else if (E->getType()->isFixedPointType()) {
11073  return EvaluateFixedPoint(E, Result, Info);
11074  }
11075  return false;
11076 }
11077 
11078 /// Check whether the given declaration can be directly converted to an integral
11079 /// rvalue. If not, no diagnostic is produced; there are other things we can
11080 /// try.
11081 bool IntExprEvaluator::CheckReferencedDecl(const Expr* E, const Decl* D) {
11082  // Enums are integer constant exprs.
11083  if (const EnumConstantDecl *ECD = dyn_cast<EnumConstantDecl>(D)) {
11084  // Check for signedness/width mismatches between E type and ECD value.
11085  bool SameSign = (ECD->getInitVal().isSigned()
11086  == E->getType()->isSignedIntegerOrEnumerationType());
11087  bool SameWidth = (ECD->getInitVal().getBitWidth()
11088  == Info.Ctx.getIntWidth(E->getType()));
11089  if (SameSign && SameWidth)
11090  return Success(ECD->getInitVal(), E);
11091  else {
11092  // Get rid of mismatch (otherwise Success assertions will fail)
11093  // by computing a new value matching the type of E.
11094  llvm::APSInt Val = ECD->getInitVal();
11095  if (!SameSign)
11096  Val.setIsSigned(!ECD->getInitVal().isSigned());
11097  if (!SameWidth)
11098  Val = Val.extOrTrunc(Info.Ctx.getIntWidth(E->getType()));
11099  return Success(Val, E);
11100  }
11101  }
11102  return false;
11103 }
11104 
11105 /// Values returned by __builtin_classify_type, chosen to match the values
11106 /// produced by GCC's builtin.
11107 enum class GCCTypeClass {
11108  None = -1,
11109  Void = 0,
11110  Integer = 1,
11111  // GCC reserves 2 for character types, but instead classifies them as
11112  // integers.
11113  Enum = 3,
11114  Bool = 4,
11115  Pointer = 5,
11116  // GCC reserves 6 for references, but appears to never use it (because
11117  // expressions never have reference type, presumably).
11118  PointerToDataMember = 7,
11119  RealFloat = 8,
11120  Complex = 9,
11121  // GCC reserves 10 for functions, but does not use it since GCC version 6 due
11122  // to decay to pointer. (Prior to version 6 it was only used in C++ mode).
11123  // GCC claims to reserve 11 for pointers to member functions, but *actually*
11124  // uses 12 for that purpose, same as for a class or struct. Maybe it
11125  // internally implements a pointer to member as a struct? Who knows.
11126  PointerToMemberFunction = 12, // Not a bug, see above.
11127  ClassOrStruct = 12,
11128  Union = 13,
11129  // GCC reserves 14 for arrays, but does not use it since GCC version 6 due to
11130  // decay to pointer. (Prior to version 6 it was only used in C++ mode).
11131  // GCC reserves 15 for strings, but actually uses 5 (pointer) for string
11132  // literals.
11133 };
11134 
11135 /// EvaluateBuiltinClassifyType - Evaluate __builtin_classify_type the same way
11136 /// as GCC.
11137 static GCCTypeClass
11138 EvaluateBuiltinClassifyType(QualType T, const LangOptions &LangOpts) {
11139  assert(!T->isDependentType() && "unexpected dependent type");
11140 
11141  QualType CanTy = T.getCanonicalType();
11142  const BuiltinType *BT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(CanTy);
11143 
11144  switch (CanTy->getTypeClass()) {
11145 #define TYPE(ID, BASE)
11146 #define DEPENDENT_TYPE(ID, BASE) case Type::ID:
11147 #define NON_CANONICAL_TYPE(ID, BASE) case Type::ID:
11148 #define NON_CANONICAL_UNLESS_DEPENDENT_TYPE(ID, BASE) case Type::ID:
11149 #include "clang/AST/TypeNodes.inc"
11150  case Type::Auto:
11151  case Type::DeducedTemplateSpecialization:
11152  llvm_unreachable("unexpected non-canonical or dependent type");
11153 
11154  case Type::Builtin:
11155  switch (BT->getKind()) {
11156 #define BUILTIN_TYPE(ID, SINGLETON_ID)
11157 #define SIGNED_TYPE(ID, SINGLETON_ID) \
11158  case BuiltinType::ID: return GCCTypeClass::Integer;
11159 #define FLOATING_TYPE(ID, SINGLETON_ID) \
11160  case BuiltinType::ID: return GCCTypeClass::RealFloat;
11161 #define PLACEHOLDER_TYPE(ID, SINGLETON_ID) \
11162  case BuiltinType::ID: break;
11163 #include "clang/AST/BuiltinTypes.def"
11164  case BuiltinType::Void:
11165  return GCCTypeClass::Void;
11166 
11167  case BuiltinType::Bool:
11168  return GCCTypeClass::Bool;
11169 
11170  case BuiltinType::Char_U:
11171  case BuiltinType::UChar:
11172  case BuiltinType::WChar_U:
11173  case BuiltinType::Char8:
11174  case BuiltinType::Char16:
11175  case BuiltinType::Char32:
11176  case BuiltinType::UShort:
11177  case BuiltinType::UInt:
11178  case BuiltinType::ULong:
11179  case BuiltinType::ULongLong:
11180  case BuiltinType::UInt128:
11181  return GCCTypeClass::Integer;
11182 
11183  case BuiltinType::UShortAccum:
11184  case BuiltinType::UAccum:
11185  case BuiltinType::ULongAccum:
11186  case BuiltinType::UShortFract:
11187  case BuiltinType::UFract:
11188  case BuiltinType::ULongFract:
11189  case BuiltinType::SatUShortAccum:
11190  case BuiltinType::SatUAccum:
11191  case BuiltinType::SatULongAccum:
11192  case BuiltinType::SatUShortFract:
11193  case BuiltinType::SatUFract:
11194  case BuiltinType::SatULongFract:
11195  return GCCTypeClass::None;
11196 
11197  case BuiltinType::NullPtr:
11198 
11199  case BuiltinType::ObjCId:
11200  case BuiltinType::ObjCClass:
11201  case BuiltinType::ObjCSel:
11202 #define IMAGE_TYPE(ImgType, Id, SingletonId, Access, Suffix) \
11203  case BuiltinType::Id:
11204 #include "clang/Basic/OpenCLImageTypes.def"
11205 #define IMAGE_TYPE(ImgType, Id, SingletonId, Access, Suffix) \
11206  case BuiltinType::Sampled##Id:
11207 #define IMAGE_WRITE_TYPE(Type, Id, Ext)
11208 #define IMAGE_READ_WRITE_TYPE(Type, Id, Ext)
11209 #include "clang/Basic/OpenCLImageTypes.def"
11210 #define EXT_OPAQUE_TYPE(ExtType, Id, Ext) \
11211  case BuiltinType::Id:
11212 #include "clang/Basic/OpenCLExtensionTypes.def"
11213  case BuiltinType::OCLSampler:
11214  case BuiltinType::OCLEvent:
11215  case BuiltinType::OCLClkEvent:
11216  case BuiltinType::OCLQueue:
11217  case BuiltinType::OCLReserveID:
11218 #define SVE_TYPE(Name, Id, SingletonId) \
11219  case BuiltinType::Id:
11220 #include "clang/Basic/AArch64SVEACLETypes.def"
11221 #define PPC_VECTOR_TYPE(Name, Id, Size) \
11222  case BuiltinType::Id:
11223 #include "clang/Basic/PPCTypes.def"
11224 #define RVV_TYPE(Name, Id, SingletonId) case BuiltinType::Id:
11225 #include "clang/Basic/RISCVVTypes.def"
11226  return GCCTypeClass::None;
11227 
11228  case BuiltinType::Dependent:
11229  llvm_unreachable("unexpected dependent type");
11230  };
11231  llvm_unreachable("unexpected placeholder type");
11232 
11233  case Type::Enum:
11234  return LangOpts.CPlusPlus ? GCCTypeClass::Enum : GCCTypeClass::Integer;
11235 
11236  case Type::Pointer:
11237  case Type::ConstantArray:
11238  case Type::VariableArray:
11239  case Type::IncompleteArray:
11240  case Type::FunctionNoProto:
11241  case Type::FunctionProto:
11242  return GCCTypeClass::Pointer;
11243 
11244  case Type::MemberPointer:
11245  return CanTy->isMemberDataPointerType()
11246  ? GCCTypeClass::PointerToDataMember
11247  : GCCTypeClass::PointerToMemberFunction;
11248 
11249  case Type::Complex:
11250  return GCCTypeClass::Complex;
11251 
11252  case Type::Record:
11253  return CanTy->isUnionType() ? GCCTypeClass::Union
11254  : GCCTypeClass::ClassOrStruct;
11255 
11256  case Type::Atomic:
11257  // GCC classifies _Atomic T the same as T.
11258  return EvaluateBuiltinClassifyType(
11259  CanTy->castAs<AtomicType>()->getValueType(), LangOpts);
11260 
11261  case Type::BlockPointer:
11262  case Type::Vector:
11263  case Type::ExtVector:
11264  case Type::ConstantMatrix:
11265  case Type::ObjCObject:
11266  case Type::ObjCInterface:
11267  case Type::ObjCObjectPointer:
11268  case Type::Pipe:
11269  case Type::BitInt:
11270  // GCC classifies vectors as None. We follow its lead and classify all
11271  // other types that don't fit into the regular classification the same way.
11272  return GCCTypeClass::None;
11273 
11274  case Type::LValueReference:
11275  case Type::RValueReference:
11276  llvm_unreachable("invalid type for expression");
11277  }
11278 
11279  llvm_unreachable("unexpected type class");
11280 }
11281 
11282 /// EvaluateBuiltinClassifyType - Evaluate __builtin_classify_type the same way
11283 /// as GCC.
11284 static GCCTypeClass
11285 EvaluateBuiltinClassifyType(const CallExpr *E, const LangOptions &LangOpts) {
11286  // If no argument was supplied, default to None. This isn't
11287  // ideal, however it is what gcc does.
11288  if (E->getNumArgs() == 0)
11289  return GCCTypeClass::None;
11290 
11291  // FIXME: Bizarrely, GCC treats a call with more than one argument as not
11292  // being an ICE, but still folds it to a constant using the type of the first
11293  // argument.
11294  return EvaluateBuiltinClassifyType(E->getArg(0)->getType(), LangOpts);
11295 }
11296 
11297 /// EvaluateBuiltinConstantPForLValue - Determine the result of
11298 /// __builtin_constant_p when applied to the given pointer.
11299 ///
11300 /// A pointer is only "constant" if it is null (or a pointer cast to integer)
11301 /// or it points to the first character of a string literal.
11302 static bool EvaluateBuiltinConstantPForLValue(const APValue &LV) {
11303  APValue::LValueBase Base = LV.getLValueBase();
11304  if (Base.isNull()) {
11305  // A null base is acceptable.
11306  return true;
11307  } else if (const Expr *E = Base.dyn_cast<const Expr *>()) {
11308  if (!isa<StringLiteral>(E))
11309  return false;
11310  return LV.getLValueOffset().isZero();
11311  } else if (Base.is<TypeInfoLValue>()) {
11312  // Surprisingly, GCC considers __builtin_constant_p(&typeid(int)) to
11313  // evaluate to true.
11314  return true;
11315  } else {
11316  // Any other base is not constant enough for GCC.
11317  return false;
11318  }
11319 }
11320 
11321 /// EvaluateBuiltinConstantP - Evaluate __builtin_constant_p as similarly to
11322 /// GCC as we can manage.
11323 static bool EvaluateBuiltinConstantP(EvalInfo &Info, const Expr *Arg) {
11324  // This evaluation is not permitted to have side-effects, so evaluate it in
11325  // a speculative evaluation context.
11326  SpeculativeEvaluationRAII SpeculativeEval(Info);
11327 
11328  // Constant-folding is always enabled for the operand of __builtin_constant_p
11329  // (even when the enclosing evaluation context otherwise requires a strict
11330  // language-specific constant expression).
11331  FoldConstant Fold(Info, true);
11332 
11333  QualType ArgType = Arg->getType();
11334 
11335  // __builtin_constant_p always has one operand. The rules which gcc follows
11336  // are not precisely documented, but are as follows:
11337  //
11338  // - If the operand is of integral, floating, complex or enumeration type,
11339  // and can be folded to a known value of that type, it returns 1.
11340  // - If the operand can be folded to a pointer to the first character
11341  // of a string literal (or such a pointer cast to an integral type)
11342  // or to a null pointer or an integer cast to a pointer, it returns 1.
11343  //
11344  // Otherwise, it returns 0.
11345  //
11346  // FIXME: GCC also intends to return 1 for literals of aggregate types, but
11347  // its support for this did not work prior to GCC 9 and is not yet well
11348  // understood.
11349  if (ArgType->isIntegralOrEnumerationType() || ArgType->isFloatingType() ||
11350  ArgType->isAnyComplexType() || ArgType->isPointerType() ||
11351  ArgType->isNullPtrType()) {
11352  APValue V;
11353  if (!::EvaluateAsRValue(Info, Arg, V) || Info.EvalStatus.HasSideEffects) {
11354  Fold.keepDiagnostics();
11355  return false;
11356  }
11357 
11358  // For a pointer (possibly cast to integer), there are special rules.
11359  if (V.getKind() == APValue::LValue)
11360  return EvaluateBuiltinConstantPForLValue(V);
11361 
11362  // Otherwise, any constant value is good enough.
11363  return V.hasValue();
11364  }
11365 
11366  // Anything else isn't considered to be sufficiently constant.
11367  return false;
11368 }
11369 
11370 /// Retrieves the "underlying object type" of the given expression,
11371 /// as used by __builtin_object_size.
11372 static QualType getObjectType(APValue::LValueBase B) {
11373  if (const ValueDecl *D = B.dyn_cast<const ValueDecl*>()) {
11374  if (const VarDecl *VD = dyn_cast<VarDecl>(D))
11375  return VD->getType();
11376  } else if (const Expr *E = B.dyn_cast<const Expr*>()) {
11377  if (isa<CompoundLiteralExpr>(E))
11378  return E->getType();
11379  } else if (B.is<TypeInfoLValue>()) {
11380  return B.getTypeInfoType();
11381  } else if (B.is<DynamicAllocLValue>()) {
11382  return B.getDynamicAllocType();
11383  }
11384 
11385  return QualType();
11386 }
11387 
11388 /// A more selective version of E->IgnoreParenCasts for
11389 /// tryEvaluateBuiltinObjectSize. This ignores some casts/parens that serve only
11390 /// to change the type of E.
11391 /// Ex. For E = `(short*)((char*)(&foo))`, returns `&foo`
11392 ///
11393 /// Always returns an RValue with a pointer representation.
11394 static const Expr *ignorePointerCastsAndParens(const Expr *E) {
11395  assert(E->isPRValue() && E->getType()->hasPointerRepresentation());
11396 
11397  auto *NoParens = E->IgnoreParens();
11398  auto *Cast = dyn_cast<CastExpr>(NoParens);
11399  if (Cast == nullptr)
11400  return NoParens;
11401 
11402  // We only conservatively allow a few kinds of casts, because this code is
11403  // inherently a simple solution that seeks to support the common case.
11404  auto CastKind = Cast->getCastKind();
11405  if (CastKind != CK_NoOp && CastKind != CK_BitCast &&
11406  CastKind != CK_AddressSpaceConversion)
11407  return NoParens;
11408 
11409  auto *SubExpr = Cast->getSubExpr();
11410  if (!SubExpr->getType()->hasPointerRepresentation() || !SubExpr->isPRValue())
11411  return NoParens;
11412  return ignorePointerCastsAndParens(SubExpr);
11413 }
11414 
11415 /// Checks to see if the given LValue's Designator is at the end of the LValue's
11416 /// record layout. e.g.
11417 /// struct { struct { int a, b; } fst, snd; } obj;
11418 /// obj.fst // no
11419 /// obj.snd // yes
11420 /// obj.fst.a // no
11421 /// obj.fst.b // no
11422 /// obj.snd.a // no
11423 /// obj.snd.b // yes
11424 ///
11425 /// Please note: this function is specialized for how __builtin_object_size
11426 /// views "objects".
11427 ///
11428 /// If this encounters an invalid RecordDecl or otherwise cannot determine the
11429 /// correct result, it will always return true.
11430 static bool isDesignatorAtObjectEnd(const ASTContext &Ctx, const LValue &LVal) {
11431  assert(!LVal.Designator.Invalid);
11432 
11433  auto IsLastOrInvalidFieldDecl = [&Ctx](const FieldDecl *FD, bool &Invalid) {
11434  const RecordDecl *Parent = FD->getParent();
11435  Invalid = Parent->isInvalidDecl();
11436  if (Invalid || Parent->isUnion())
11437  return true;
11438  const ASTRecordLayout &Layout = Ctx.getASTRecordLayout(Parent);
11439  return FD->getFieldIndex() + 1 == Layout.getFieldCount();
11440  };
11441 
11442  auto &Base = LVal.getLValueBase();
11443  if (auto *ME = dyn_cast_or_null<MemberExpr>(Base.dyn_cast<const Expr *>())) {
11444  if (auto *FD = dyn_cast<FieldDecl>(ME->getMemberDecl())) {
11445  bool Invalid;
11446  if (!IsLastOrInvalidFieldDecl(FD, Invalid))
11447  return Invalid;
11448  } else if (auto *IFD = dyn_cast<IndirectFieldDecl>(ME->getMemberDecl())) {
11449  for (auto *FD : IFD->chain()) {
11450  bool Invalid;
11451  if (!IsLastOrInvalidFieldDecl(cast<FieldDecl>(FD), Invalid))
11452  return Invalid;
11453  }
11454  }
11455  }
11456 
11457  unsigned I = 0;
11458  QualType BaseType = getType(Base);
11459  if (LVal.Designator.FirstEntryIsAnUnsizedArray) {
11460  // If we don't know the array bound, conservatively assume we're looking at
11461  // the final array element.
11462  ++I;
11463  if (BaseType->isIncompleteArrayType())
11464  BaseType = Ctx.getAsArrayType(BaseType)->getElementType();
11465  else
11466  BaseType = BaseType->castAs<PointerType>()->getPointeeType();
11467  }
11468 
11469  for (unsigned E = LVal.Designator.Entries.size(); I != E; ++I) {
11470  const auto &Entry = LVal.Designator.Entries[I];
11471  if (BaseType->isArrayType()) {
11472  // Because __builtin_object_size treats arrays as objects, we can ignore
11473  // the index iff this is the last array in the Designator.
11474  if (I + 1 == E)
11475  return true;
11476  const auto *CAT = cast<ConstantArrayType>(Ctx.getAsArrayType(BaseType));
11477  uint64_t Index = Entry.getAsArrayIndex();
11478  if (Index + 1 != CAT->getSize())
11479  return false;
11480  BaseType = CAT->getElementType();
11481  } else if (BaseType->isAnyComplexType()) {
11482  const auto *CT = BaseType->castAs<ComplexType>();
11483  uint64_t Index = Entry.getAsArrayIndex();
11484  if (Index != 1)
11485  return false;
11486  BaseType = CT->getElementType();
11487  } else if (auto *FD = getAsField(Entry)) {
11488  bool Invalid;
11489  if (!IsLastOrInvalidFieldDecl(FD, Invalid))
11490  return Invalid;
11491  BaseType = FD->getType();
11492  } else {
11493  assert(getAsBaseClass(Entry) && "Expecting cast to a base class");
11494  return false;
11495  }
11496  }
11497  return true;
11498 }
11499 
11500 /// Tests to see if the LValue has a user-specified designator (that isn't
11501 /// necessarily valid). Note that this always returns 'true' if the LValue has
11502 /// an unsized array as its first designator entry, because there's currently no
11503 /// way to tell if the user typed *foo or foo[0].
11504 static bool refersToCompleteObject(const LValue &LVal) {
11505  if (LVal.Designator.Invalid)
11506  return false;
11507 
11508  if (!LVal.Designator.Entries.empty())
11509  return LVal.Designator.isMostDerivedAnUnsizedArray();
11510 
11511  if (!LVal.InvalidBase)
11512  return true;
11513 
11514  // If `E` is a MemberExpr, then the first part of the designator is hiding in
11515  // the LValueBase.
11516  const auto *E = LVal.Base.dyn_cast<const Expr *>();
11517  return !E || !isa<MemberExpr>(E);
11518 }
11519 
11520 /// Attempts to detect a user writing into a piece of memory that's impossible
11521 /// to figure out the size of by just using types.
11522 static bool isUserWritingOffTheEnd(const ASTContext &Ctx, const LValue &LVal) {
11523  const SubobjectDesignator &Designator = LVal.Designator;
11524  // Notes:
11525  // - Users can only write off of the end when we have an invalid base. Invalid
11526  // bases imply we don't know where the memory came from.
11527  // - We used to be a bit more aggressive here; we'd only be conservative if
11528  // the array at the end was flexible, or if it had 0 or 1 elements. This
11529  // broke some common standard library extensions (PR30346), but was
11530  // otherwise seemingly fine. It may be useful to reintroduce this behavior
11531  // with some sort of list. OTOH, it seems that GCC is always
11532  // conservative with the last element in structs (if it's an array), so our
11533  // current behavior is more compatible than an explicit list approach would
11534  // be.
11535  return LVal.InvalidBase &&
11536  Designator.Entries.size() == Designator.MostDerivedPathLength &&
11537  Designator.MostDerivedIsArrayElement &&
11538  isDesignatorAtObjectEnd(Ctx, LVal);
11539 }
11540 
11541 /// Converts the given APInt to CharUnits, assuming the APInt is unsigned.
11542 /// Fails if the conversion would cause loss of precision.
11543 static bool convertUnsignedAPIntToCharUnits(const llvm::APInt &Int,
11544  CharUnits &Result) {
11545  auto CharUnitsMax = std::numeric_limits<CharUnits::QuantityType>::max();
11546  if (Int.ugt(CharUnitsMax))
11547  return false;
11548  Result = CharUnits::fromQuantity(Int.getZExtValue());
11549  return true;
11550 }
11551 
11552 /// Helper for tryEvaluateBuiltinObjectSize -- Given an LValue, this will
11553 /// determine how many bytes exist from the beginning of the object to either
11554 /// the end of the current subobject, or the end of the object itself, depending
11555 /// on what the LValue looks like + the value of Type.
11556 ///
11557 /// If this returns false, the value of Result is undefined.
11558 static bool determineEndOffset(EvalInfo &Info, SourceLocation ExprLoc,
11559  unsigned Type, const LValue &LVal,
11560  CharUnits &EndOffset) {
11561  bool DetermineForCompleteObject = refersToCompleteObject(LVal);
11562 
11563  auto CheckedHandleSizeof = [&](QualType Ty, CharUnits &Result) {
11564  if (Ty.isNull() || Ty->isIncompleteType() || Ty->isFunctionType())
11565  return false;
11566  return HandleSizeof(Info, ExprLoc, Ty, Result);
11567  };
11568 
11569  // We want to evaluate the size of the entire object. This is a valid fallback
11570  // for when Type=1 and the designator is invalid, because we're asked for an
11571  // upper-bound.
11572  if (!(Type & 1) || LVal.Designator.Invalid || DetermineForCompleteObject) {
11573  // Type=3 wants a lower bound, so we can't fall back to this.
11574  if (Type == 3 && !DetermineForCompleteObject)
11575  return false;
11576 
11577  llvm::APInt APEndOffset;
11578  if (isBaseAnAllocSizeCall(LVal.getLValueBase()) &&
11579  getBytesReturnedByAllocSizeCall(Info.Ctx, LVal, APEndOffset))
11580  return convertUnsignedAPIntToCharUnits(APEndOffset, EndOffset);
11581 
11582  if (LVal.InvalidBase)
11583  return false;
11584 
11585  QualType BaseTy = getObjectType(LVal.getLValueBase());
11586  return CheckedHandleSizeof(BaseTy, EndOffset);
11587  }
11588 
11589  // We want to evaluate the size of a subobject.
11590  const SubobjectDesignator &Designator = LVal.Designator;
11591 
11592  // The following is a moderately common idiom in C:
11593  //
11594  // struct Foo { int a; char c[1]; };
11595  // struct Foo *F = (struct Foo *)malloc(sizeof(struct Foo) + strlen(Bar));
11596  // strcpy(&F->c[0], Bar);
11597  //
11598  // In order to not break too much legacy code, we need to support it.
11599  if (isUserWritingOffTheEnd(Info.Ctx, LVal)) {
11600  // If we can resolve this to an alloc_size call, we can hand that back,
11601  // because we know for certain how many bytes there are to write to.
11602  llvm::APInt APEndOffset;
11603  if (isBaseAnAllocSizeCall(LVal.getLValueBase()) &&
11604  getBytesReturnedByAllocSizeCall(Info.Ctx, LVal, APEndOffset))
11605  return convertUnsignedAPIntToCharUnits(APEndOffset, EndOffset);
11606 
11607  // If we cannot determine the size of the initial allocation, then we can't
11608  // given an accurate upper-bound. However, we are still able to give
11609  // conservative lower-bounds for Type=3.
11610  if (Type == 1)
11611  return false;
11612  }
11613 
11614  CharUnits BytesPerElem;
11615  if (!CheckedHandleSizeof(Designator.MostDerivedType, BytesPerElem))
11616  return false;
11617 
11618  // According to the GCC documentation, we want the size of the subobject
11619  // denoted by the pointer. But that's not quite right -- what we actually
11620  // want is the size of the immediately-enclosing array, if there is one.
11621  int64_t ElemsRemaining;
11622  if (Designator.MostDerivedIsArrayElement &&
11623  Designator.Entries.size() == Designator.MostDerivedPathLength) {
11624  uint64_t ArraySize = Designator.getMostDerivedArraySize();
11625  uint64_t ArrayIndex = Designator.Entries.back().getAsArrayIndex();
11626  ElemsRemaining = ArraySize <= ArrayIndex ? 0 : ArraySize - ArrayIndex;
11627  } else {
11628  ElemsRemaining = Designator.isOnePastTheEnd() ? 0 : 1;
11629  }
11630 
11631  EndOffset = LVal.getLValueOffset() + BytesPerElem * ElemsRemaining;
11632  return true;
11633 }
11634 
11635 /// Tries to evaluate the __builtin_object_size for @p E. If successful,
11636 /// returns true and stores the result in @p Size.
11637 ///
11638 /// If @p WasError is non-null, this will report whether the failure to evaluate
11639 /// is to be treated as an Error in IntExprEvaluator.
11640 static bool tryEvaluateBuiltinObjectSize(const Expr *E, unsigned Type,
11641  EvalInfo &Info, uint64_t &Size) {
11642  // Determine the denoted object.
11643  LValue LVal;
11644  {
11645  // The operand of __builtin_object_size is never evaluated for side-effects.
11646  // If there are any, but we can determine the pointed-to object anyway, then
11647  // ignore the side-effects.
11648  SpeculativeEvaluationRAII SpeculativeEval(Info);
11649  IgnoreSideEffectsRAII Fold(Info);
11650 
11651  if (E->isGLValue()) {
11652  // It's possible for us to be given GLValues if we're called via
11653  // Expr::tryEvaluateObjectSize.
11654  APValue RVal;
11655  if (!EvaluateAsRValue(Info, E, RVal))
11656  return false;
11657  LVal.setFrom(Info.Ctx, RVal);
11658  } else if (!EvaluatePointer(ignorePointerCastsAndParens(E), LVal, Info,
11659  /*InvalidBaseOK=*/true))
11660  return false;
11661  }
11662 
11663  // If we point to before the start of the object, there are no accessible
11664  // bytes.
11665  if (LVal.getLValueOffset().isNegative()) {
11666  Size = 0;
11667  return true;
11668  }
11669 
11670  CharUnits EndOffset;
11671  if (!determineEndOffset(Info, E->getExprLoc(), Type, LVal, EndOffset))
11672  return false;
11673 
11674  // If we've fallen outside of the end offset, just pretend there's nothing to
11675  // write to/read from.
11676  if (EndOffset <= LVal.getLValueOffset())
11677  Size = 0;
11678  else
11679  Size = (EndOffset - LVal.getLValueOffset()).getQuantity();
11680  return true;
11681 }
11682 
11683 bool IntExprEvaluator::VisitCallExpr(const CallExpr *E) {
11684  if (unsigned BuiltinOp = E->getBuiltinCallee())
11685  return VisitBuiltinCallExpr(E, BuiltinOp);
11686 
11687  return ExprEvaluatorBaseTy::VisitCallExpr(E);
11688 }
11689 
11690 static bool getBuiltinAlignArguments(const CallExpr *E, EvalInfo &Info,
11691  APValue &Val, APSInt &Alignment) {
11692  QualType SrcTy = E->getArg(0)->getType();
11693  if (!getAlignmentArgument(E->getArg(1), SrcTy, Info, Alignment))
11694  return false;
11695  // Even though we are evaluating integer expressions we could get a pointer
11696  // argument for the __builtin_is_aligned() case.
11697  if (SrcTy->isPointerType()) {
11698  LValue Ptr;
11699  if (!EvaluatePointer(E->getArg(0), Ptr, Info))
11700  return false;
11701  Ptr.moveInto(Val);
11702  } else if (!SrcTy->isIntegralOrEnumerationType()) {
11703  Info.FFDiag(E->getArg(0));
11704  return false;
11705  } else {
11706  APSInt SrcInt;
11707  if (!EvaluateInteger(E->getArg(0), SrcInt, Info))
11708  return false;
11709  assert(SrcInt.getBitWidth() >= Alignment.getBitWidth() &&
11710  "Bit widths must be the same");
11711  Val = APValue(SrcInt);
11712  }
11713  assert(Val.hasValue());
11714  return true;
11715 }
11716 
11717 bool IntExprEvaluator::VisitBuiltinCallExpr(const CallExpr *E,
11718  unsigned BuiltinOp) {
11719  switch (BuiltinOp) {
11720  default:
11721  return ExprEvaluatorBaseTy::VisitCallExpr(E);
11722 
11723  case Builtin::BI__builtin_dynamic_object_size:
11724  case Builtin::BI__builtin_object_size: {
11725  // The type was checked when we built the expression.
11726  unsigned Type =
11727  E->getArg(1)->EvaluateKnownConstInt(Info.Ctx).getZExtValue();
11728  assert(Type <= 3 && "unexpected type");
11729 
11730  uint64_t Size;
11731  if (tryEvaluateBuiltinObjectSize(E->getArg(0), Type, Info, Size))
11732  return Success(Size, E);
11733 
11734  if (E->getArg(0)->HasSideEffects(Info.Ctx))
11735  return Success((Type & 2) ? 0 : -1, E);
11736 
11737  // Expression had no side effects, but we couldn't statically determine the
11738  // size of the referenced object.
11739  switch (Info.EvalMode) {
11740  case EvalInfo::EM_ConstantExpression:
11741  case EvalInfo::EM_ConstantFold:
11742  case EvalInfo::EM_IgnoreSideEffects:
11743  // Leave it to IR generation.
11744  return Error(E);
11745  case EvalInfo::EM_ConstantExpressionUnevaluated:
11746  // Reduce it to a constant now.
11747  return Success((Type & 2) ? 0 : -1, E);
11748  }
11749 
11750  llvm_unreachable("unexpected EvalMode");
11751  }
11752 
11753  case Builtin::BI__builtin_os_log_format_buffer_size: {
11754  analyze_os_log::OSLogBufferLayout Layout;
11755  analyze_os_log::computeOSLogBufferLayout(Info.Ctx, E, Layout);
11756  return Success(Layout.size().getQuantity(), E);
11757  }
11758 
11759  case Builtin::BI__builtin_is_aligned: {
11760  APValue Src;
11761  APSInt Alignment;
11762  if (!getBuiltinAlignArguments(E, Info, Src, Alignment))
11763  return false;
11764  if (Src.isLValue()) {
11765  // If we evaluated a pointer, check the minimum known alignment.
11766  LValue Ptr;
11767  Ptr.setFrom(Info.Ctx, Src);
11768  CharUnits BaseAlignment = getBaseAlignment(Info, Ptr);
11769  CharUnits PtrAlign = BaseAlignment.alignmentAtOffset(Ptr.Offset);
11770  // We can return true if the known alignment at the computed offset is
11771  // greater than the requested alignment.
11772  assert(PtrAlign.isPowerOfTwo());
11773  assert(Alignment.isPowerOf2());
11774  if (PtrAlign.getQuantity() >= Alignment)
11775  return Success(1, E);
11776  // If the alignment is not known to be sufficient, some cases could still
11777  // be aligned at run time. However, if the requested alignment is less or
11778  // equal to the base alignment and the offset is not aligned, we know that
11779  // the run-time value can never be aligned.
11780  if (BaseAlignment.getQuantity() >= Alignment &&
11781  PtrAlign.getQuantity() < Alignment)
11782  return Success(0, E);
11783  // Otherwise we can't infer whether the value is sufficiently aligned.
11784  // TODO: __builtin_is_aligned(__builtin_align_{down,up{(expr, N), N)
11785  // in cases where we can't fully evaluate the pointer.
11786  Info.FFDiag(E->getArg(0), diag::note_constexpr_alignment_compute)
11787  << Alignment;
11788  return false;
11789  }
11790  assert(Src.isInt());
11791  return Success((Src.getInt() & (Alignment - 1)) == 0 ? 1 : 0, E);
11792  }
11793  case Builtin::BI__builtin_align_up: {
11794  APValue Src;
11795  APSInt Alignment;
11796  if (!getBuiltinAlignArguments(E, Info, Src, Alignment))
11797  return false;
11798  if (!Src.isInt())
11799  return Error(E);
11800  APSInt AlignedVal =
11801  APSInt((Src.getInt() + (Alignment - 1)) & ~(Alignment - 1),
11802  Src.getInt().isUnsigned());
11803  assert(AlignedVal.getBitWidth() == Src.getInt().getBitWidth());
11804  return Success(AlignedVal, E);
11805  }
11806  case Builtin::BI__builtin_align_down: {
11807  APValue Src;
11808  APSInt Alignment;
11809  if (!getBuiltinAlignArguments(E, Info, Src, Alignment))
11810  return false;
11811  if (!Src.isInt())
11812  return Error(E);
11813  APSInt AlignedVal =
11814  APSInt(Src.getInt() & ~(Alignment - 1), Src.getInt().isUnsigned());
11815  assert(AlignedVal.getBitWidth() == Src.getInt().getBitWidth());
11816  return Success(AlignedVal, E);
11817  }

12000  case Builtin::BI__builtin_rotateleft64:

12031  case Builtin::BIstrlen:

12037  << (std::string("'") + Info.Ctx.BuiltinInfo.getName(BuiltinOp) + "'");

12041  case Builtin::BI__builtin_strlen:
